1. "Miss Sara Sampson" (original spelling "Miß Sara Sampson"), a play written in 1755, which is considered one of the first bourgeois tragedies and marked Gotthold Ephraim Lessing's first real success as a playwright. It premiered in Frankfurt-on-the-Oder and was later translated and performed in France with success.

2. "Emilia Galotti," a play in five acts that premiered on 8 March 1772 in Brunswick ("Braunschweig" in German). This work is a classic example of German "bürgerliches Trauerspiel" (bourgeois tragedy), drawing inspiration from the Roman myth of Verginia and belonging to the same category as Schiller's "Kabale und Liebe" and Hebbel's "Maria Magdalene."
